                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">881.00/926: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-06-06T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 6, 1924—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. Department’s 23, June 4, 5 p.m.<note n="7" xml:id="d387fn7">See footnote 3,
                            <ref target="#pg_456">p. 456</ref>.</note> Tangier convention.
                    Confidentially informed by Foreign Office that Portuguese Government will
                    presently “ratify” the convention without conditions or reservations and has
                    same attitude toward port concession.</p>
                <p>Foreign Office states that Portugal found convention unsatisfactory and would
                    have preferred larger representation, at least two, but decided after careful
                    study that under existing circumstances unconditional adhesion was best. …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
